segments.text: okay my name is roger galatis and i'm president of the woodlands corporation i've been with the woodlands corporation now since february 1979 and had an opportunity to participate in the growth of the woodlands during that period of time and also

Prior to 1979, I lived in the local area, worked for a competing real estate development company whose name is Friendswood Development Company, a subsidiary of Exxon, and had an opportunity to watch the weapons grow from its beginning and monitored and participated in that growth through its 16-year history.
history to this point.
The Woodlands is 16 years old October 19th.
Everything you see here today and what you will encounter has occurred in 16 years.
Remarkable.
Now, in Friendswood, in terms of what Friendswood was doing as compared to what Woodlands... Well, Friendswood and all the company is wholly owned subsidiary of Exxon Corporation.
And they have developed large-scale communities in Houston, Clear Lake City, which is where the NASA Space Center is located.
And actually, it was the first large-scale plane community to be developed in the Houston region.
That started in the late 50s, actually, and active development work in the early and mid-60s.
The second large community that Princewood developed was a joint venture with King Ranch.
And it's called Kingwood, which is located 25 miles to the east of the Woodlands.
Both of those very large scale, similar in nature to the Woodlands in terms of scope and size and life expectancy and those kinds of things.
So I had some reference to judge what was happening in the Woodlands in the early days and to make the move to the Woodlands when I first
came in contact with George Mitchell.
And then when and how was that?
Well, I was happily working for Friendswood, and I got a call one day from an executive search firm, and the question was, would you like to join the Woodlands development?
And my first answer was, no, I'm happy where I am.
Well, that conversation went on for a while.
The short story is that after several conversations, I elected to
to join the Woodlands, and that was in 1979.
I've been here continuously since that time.
Have you contacted George Mitchell, had conversations with him before that decision, personally?
I knew George Mitchell by reputation, not personally, and I knew the Woodlands by observation, and I knew a number of the people who lived and worked in the Woodlands.
I had some knowledge of what was happening, but no personal knowledge of Mr. Mitchell and his
a visionary approach and enthusiasm for doing things in a visionary way.
So that's not what brought you into this firm?
No, it was not that per se.

I guess one of the things that was intriguing about coming to the Woodlands was the fact that it was in Montgomery County, the county where I established home, a place I wanted to remain probably for the rest of my life.
It was at the stage of development where a lot of potential existed for the future, and I thought the timing was good to make that move.
Did you move in as president?
Yeah, president.
No.

Originally, I came to the Woodlands and was responsible for the residential part of the development here, the residential community, which includes all the infrastructure and support structures and support structure for
the residents who live here, including schools and churches and that kind of infrastructure.
I originally became his senior vice president of residential development.
Later became executive vice president of the company, and then in 1986 became president of the company.
You know George Mitchell now.
Very well.
Yeah, I would imagine so.
You must have a feel for what it is he wanted you to do.
As you got promoted through the company, you must have a sense of, I don't want to call it an agenda, but he obviously had certain things that he had you in mind to do.
Well, George is a person who has a great vision for the future.
And sometimes it takes lesser men a longer period of time to understand what that vision is.
But George's enthusiasm never wanes.
George never loses a battle.
Maybe he's not yet won it, but he's never lost it.
And the former chancellor at Texas A&M,
I'm not sure if that's the right word.
I'm not sure if that's the right word.
I'm not sure if that's the right word.
I'm not sure if that's the right word.
I'm not sure if that's the right word.
today are already solved.
They may not like the solution, but nonetheless, they're solved.
And he's thinking about 30 years down the road.
And that describes Georgia about as well as any attempt to describe Georgia I've heard.
And it's impressed me since I've heard Frank make that statement.
I made a talk one time, and I said working for George Mitchell is fairly simple.
What you need to do is do it with integrity, do it with quality, make sure you save the trees and natural vegetation, and do it right now.
If you do those things, you're in pretty good shape with George.
I think that's a consistent formula.
I would guess you... George is not inconsistent.
George is very consistent in his approach.
One of the things George does and insists that this company do, and I think it's a tribute to him that's comfortable for us, is we put a lot back into this community.
We expect to make a profit.
We're in the business to make a profit.

But there are many things that we do as a development company that puts value back into the community that has long-lasting effects and will have long-lasting effects on this community for years and years to come.
but maybe a typical developer in other places might not do.
For example, there's a program of art in public places, and as you drive through the community, you will see major works of art that's been installed in public esplanades or in your building.
I think we have about 13 pieces of major artwork now that have been funded both by the development company and by other companies who bought land from us and built buildings.
We set aside a portion of our
land sales revenue and a portion of the cost of constructing the building into an art fund.
And that fund is used to not only acquire art pieces, but also to maintain those that have been acquired over time.

We also just finished building and developing the Cynthia Woods Natural Center for Performing Arts in the Woodlands, which is about a $10 million contribution that obviously is going to add value to the community.
add value to the remaining lands we have to develop and sell.
But it's something that didn't have to be done.
It's something George wanted to do.
He felt very strongly that it needs to be a regional asset for the city of Houston as well as the woodlands in Montgomery County.
And this past year we had probably, in its first year of operations, 30 different performances there that include the ballet, the symphony,
contemporary music, country music, a whole array of programs, and more than 200,000 people came to attend those 20 to 30 performances, an average of 6,000 people for each performance.
What was your vision for the women when you joined this company?
Did you see it as something really different from what you've been doing?
Well, the Woodlands is probably more comprehensive than most other large-scale communities in the Houston region and is as comprehensive as any in the country.
There are only five, six, maybe 10 places in the country where a community like this is being developed in a comprehensive nature.
So it's a unique employment opportunity.
It gives you national exposure.

international recognition not not just as an individual but the community and the quality of what's being done here is recognized as being quality one thing i see during here in the traditional review community concept is in fact this idea of the economic community yeah and i sense that maybe this is one of your special for us well explain how that's being developed early on we we

We recognized clearly we were not just in the real estate development business, but we had to be in the economic development business if we were to succeed, which is different from some other large-scale communities.
We started out, in fact, with a large residential component, a recreational component.
But simultaneously with that, we
set about the mission of developing jobs in the local community.
When did that come along?
Was that already part of the program when you came in?
Yeah, it was in the fledgling stage.
We've expanded it over the 12 years I've been here.
But that was part of the mission.
Our goal and objective is to create jobs along with housing and residential population.
Right now we have close to 8,000 permanent jobs in the Woodlands.
The original objective was to have
one job for every household in the Woodlands.
Today we have about 11,500 households and 8,000 jobs.
But we also have about 2,000 retirement units in the Woodlands.
So if you take those out of the workforce, we're pretty close to imbalance.
And I think the very impressive thing about that is we've been able to create those jobs during a period of time when Houston lost 200,000 jobs in its economy.
Let's talk about the 1980s now.
Okay, the 1980s.
You're here in 1979, you're here, and the economy is just about to go into a... Well, starting in 1980, late in 79, through 1982, the Houston economy, the Texas economy, was very robust.
Frankly, I guess we went through a period of arrogance in Texas, and
developed a reputation which was deserved but not very pleasing in other parts of the country.
The price of oil was escalating and energy was keying.
Jobs were being created in the Houston economy at the rate of 65,000, 70,000 jobs a year.
The population was growing at 90,000 a year.
Tremendous need for housing, tremendous need for office buildings, tremendous need for shopping and support services.
And frankly, a lot of things could be built without much thought given the quality of life and those kinds of things.
And then in 1982, when the first decline in oil prices became apparent, some of that robust nature of the economy started drifting away.
And by 1986, things were really pretty bad in the Houston economy as well as throughout the state of Texas.

And it became quite apparent that if we were going to compete on a national scale and attract businesses into the Houston region and diversify our economy and get away from being 80% dependent on energy and try to bring in companies like Compaq Computer and biotechnology firms and things that would give us a broader economic base, we were going to have to pay attention as a city, as a region.
We were going to have to pay attention to the quality of life issues.
And that really played into the hands of the Woodlands very nicely, because from the outset, we were, our mission was to deal with quality of life.
And back in 1982, we sold in the Woodlands, if I recall, as one measure of activity, I think we sold 1000 new homes that year.
But we only had 2.8% of the housing market in Houston.
In the downturn in 1987-88,
which was about the bottom of it.
We were selling maybe 500 homes in Houston, but we had captured maybe 10% or 11% of the total market.
So while absolute numbers had declined, our market share had grown tremendously.

And today, the five large-scale communities in Houston capture about 40% of the housing market in Houston, which says that in five locations, almost one out of every two new home sales made in Houston

in those five locations and those five locations while they differ in scope and size and somewhat in approach they do address quality of life issues and i think the lack of zoning in houston and the ability of these large-scale communities to through restrictive covenants in in effect establishes the zoning so that people would know where the shopping centers are going to be and the apartments are going to be and the single-family housing are going to be

coupled with the mission of creating jobs in the local community and enhancing the mobility to get from this location to other job locations for those who did not work here, greatly enhanced the position of the woodlands and the other large-scale communities in the Houston region.
Let me interrupt for a second and ask a question.
You mentioned that in the downturn,
I don't want to put words in your mouth, but what I'm hearing you say is that the Woodlands was appropriately positioned to take advantage of quality of life issues.
The quality of life issue has been something from the inception.
That's right.
We've heard.
Right.
Did you, at the same time, though, I mean, was this a passive thing?
Did you just reap a benefit, or in fact, was there some sort of marketing effort, aggressive or low-key, to go out and sell
the concept of the Woodlands to other parts of the country?
No.
We aggressively marketed the product that we were building.
And we were able to more clearly focus on the quality of life issues in that marketing approach.
And we did things beyond marketing.
Marketing is sort of an all-encompassing word.
It includes selling.
It includes advertising.
But it also includes building a product.
And I think we were building the product was the main thing.

We have planted the seed that led toward the development of the hospital in the Woodlands, which provided a delivery for health services in this local community and in this region surrounding the Woodlands.
We also followed that same model and have assisted in the development of a private college preparatory school here in the Woodlands called the John Cooper School.
We donated land.
guaranteed some of the financing for the first building to be constructed.
We helped recruit the faculty and helped identify key board members to serve on a nonprofit corporation that owns it.
Now, that does a couple of things for you.
One, it expresses clearly your involvement in quality of life issues and your concern for education, the elevation of the educational standards.
But in addition to that, it helps you to attract businesses here

particularly in the high-tech area, in the biotechnology and the medical field, which we actively pursued through the involvement of the Texas Medical Center, because those people are interested in quality education for their children, and they're more likely to live in an environment where that educational opportunity is available, where quality housing is available, a broad cross-section of housing opportunities are here, and medical services are available.
But you have gotten cooperation and support from the Texas Medical Center, not competition in terms of that.
Well, Texas Medical, institutions in the Texas Medical Center is separate and apart from the Texas Medical Center, which is a nonprofit corporation itself.
We've dealt with Baylor College of Medicine, University of Texas Health Science Center, now MD Anderson.
And all of those have a presence here in the Woodlands.

an interesting thing that happened in this diversification effort in texas in the houston region before the downturn occurred the texas medical center engaged in tremendous research programs they wrote about those research programs published it in the england journal of medicine and other companies uh pharmaceutical companies in other parts of the country and overseas
Europe and Japan particularly, took those academic findings and converted that to a product or a process that created commercial growth.
And George Mitchell had the notion that that could happen right here in Houston, Texas, and more particularly here in the Woodlands.
And he formed a venture capital company to help medical schools fund startup companies so that they could develop
and benefit from their academic work in a commercial field.
And that benefited the Woodlands because we could build buildings to house that activity.
The scientists would live here in the Woodlands and they would buy homes here.
So it was, I think, a very good marriage that once again came out of the position of George Mitchell and his willingness to invest funds to make it happen.
Did this basically start with a hospital and then started to expand?
No, the hospital came along.
The hospital actually was a separate initiative, not directly tied to the medical research in the medical center.
It was tied to the clinical aspects of the medical center.
And it was needed actually to help deliver it.
In the early days, 1975, 76, 77, a group of people in the Woodlands
came together, and this is what's nice about the Woodlands.
The developer doesn't have to do everything here.
It's the quality people who come in and make this a very special place.
Given the chance, they'll solve a lot of their own problems and give them some initiatives and encouragement.

But a group of people came together and formed something called the Woodlands Medical Center, Inc. And they had this question, how do we provide medical services for a growing community that one day will be 150,000 people?
And it started out with the vision of having a clinic with two beds in it so that you could have outpatient services.
And that notion grew into a 100-bed hospital before it was constructed.
But this was outside the framework of the Women's Corporation.
Well, we were deeply involved in it.
We were involved in it.
I spent eight years of my life working on it.
But that was the facility that really took the initiative.
We had a nonprofit corporation with a board of directors
comprised of people who lived in this community and also some people who were associated with Baylor College of Medicine and Methodist Hospital.
And through that nucleus of people and some funding on our behalf and some planning that we put into it, we now have a hundred bed hospital operating here.
It's a non-profit corporation.
And that same model was used to develop the private school.
Okay, so that's sort of a style of management, isn't it?
Right.
Right.
And that evolved, you know, you learn as you go along.

One other significant element that has occurred here that involves Texas A&M in the University of Texas, University of Houston, was the formation of the, then the Houston Area Research Center, which modified its name to the Houston Advanced Research Center, still using the acronym HART.
But that's modeled after the research triangle in North Carolina.
When
And North Carolina looked at itself and its economic futures.
Back in the 60s, they tried to assess what their strengths were.
And the tobacco industry was going down, agriculture was going down.
But they had a strong involvement of academic institutions and a need for research.
So they formed this 5,000-acre block of land called the Research Triangle.
It is a triangle, actually, between the University of North Carolina and the North Carolina State and Duke.
And they formed something very similar to HART, which is the Research Triangle Institute.
And it was the nucleus that has led to the development of more than 30,000 jobs in that location now.
And the world-renowned for its research activities and high-tech manufacturing there.

facilities i guess ibm is the largest singular employer there what was the initiative behind the park were you involved in that yeah i was involved in it on the periphery george mitchell once again had the notion that had the bulldog determination to make it work willing to put some of his personal funds into it to make it work the company donated agreed to donate 100 acres of land for our campus upon which it would be built and

provided some of the initial funding for the first several buildings that were built and now it once again is a freestanding non-profit corporation not under the control and direction anyway of the woodlands corporation but it is here in the woodland and it does things that benefits the community do you have a sense it sounds to me like what you're saying is the strategic planning occurs in the head of your commission well a lot of the initiative comes from that we've
We try to put it into a strategic plan that can be implemented.
But he's a part of a lot of the vision that has gone into this place.
Do you have a sense or an opinion of the beauty of what you've described is the plan already existed.
It becomes more important because of some economic
turmoil in Texas.
The notion to diversify the Houston economy, of course, is also going to benefit the woodlands tremendously.
And these other policies that have developed, such as the attempt to get a portion of the University of Houston campus here, the HART, all these other kind of things, all feed into the same goal.
I guess what I'd like to know is, or it would be interesting to ascertain your sense of
of how you fit into that strategic planning matrix.
You're involved also in policies.
What we're trying to do is, as we interview people, identify what's the contribution of this individual toward
for the whole that is becoming the woodlands.
And for all time and eternity, someone's going to say, you know, Roger Galatis did A, B, C. Where do you fit?
Well, I guess I would have to say that I'm deeply involved in the overall planning and development process.
as it relates to the day-to-day functions that take place in this community.
I have a deep involvement personally with people in the community.
This community is not going to be any stronger than the fabric that holds it together.
And I guess if I have a sense of mission myself, it's to make sure that the institutions that are put in place fit into the overall strategy of what's being accomplished here in the woodlands.
We work closely with churches.
We work closely with community groups.
We work closely with the schools.
We work closely with things like the Lions Club and their fundraising activities.
We work closely with the YMCA.
I was personally involved in helping bring the YMCA, a regional YMCA, into the Woodlands.
I serve on the board of the private school and the board of the hospital, and I guess
My function is to make sure this grand strategy is implemented in a timely and effective way.
I would like to think I add something to that vision, but when placed against Mr. Mitchell's vision, I guess few of us here would reach to those great heights.
I say that.
But you implement.
Yeah, and there are a lot of us implementing.
I'm not sure.

George's visions, I don't mind saying this on tape, and I don't mind you writing it down so George can hear it, but I only wish I was doing about 20% of the things that George Mitchell thinks I'm doing.
He's a very stimulating individual, and he has a...
He says if you're not working on five or six things at one time, you're not being productive.
And we all have...
It's a challenge to accomplish all the things that George would like to have accomplished in the timeframe that he thinks would be appropriate and suitable.
But he also is a very understanding individual, and he's compassionate, sometimes not understood by everyone that comes in contact with him initially, because he is thinking about the future.
And so many of us are focused on today's problem.
When you see these things, such as the medical park, I guess, and the research park, and the Cooper School, are you essentially putting a ship out at sea to see what's going to happen, I guess?
No, I think we have a rudder on the ship.
I think we have a sense of direction.
And sometimes when we start, though, we don't know exactly how we're going to get there.
exactly what form it's going to take.
I don't think that's necessarily a condemnation of the management of this place.
Sometimes you just don't have all the answers.
You don't know where you'd like to get to, what you'd like the mission to be, what you'd like to accomplish, but you're really not sure how you're going to get there, how it's all going to be funded.
I think if you took time to understand all that, you may not get there.
Is that, in fact, the uniqueness of the woodlands?
You mentioned Kingwood, which is a completely different type of community.
I mean, it's a nice community, but it's a completely different.
Yeah, I worked there for a long time.
Yeah, but the orientation of just driving through the place, it's totally different.
Is the uniqueness of the woodlands this emphasis on infrastructure, what you're talking about?
Is that really what sets it apart from?
Well, I think there's several things it sets it apart.
One, I can kind of list them in.
This is not saying we're better or they're better, but it's an observation of differences.
One, we work much more diligently to preserve the natural environment, natural vegetation.
You drive into the woodlands and you don't see 30,000 people.
You don't see 5,000 square feet of non-residential space.
You don't see 12,000 homes.
You don't see a conference center.
And to the people who live here, they really like that.
To some people who see it for the first time, they don't understand it, and it's not traditional.
It's a marketing challenge, frankly, because people, when they're moving into the Houston region, they like things that they have seen in other places and they relate to them.

But if we can get a shot at them and talk to them for a while and let them talk to people who live here, they will understand that this natural environment and natural vegetation is really dysfunctional.
It serves to eliminate the stormwater runoff.
It forms more water.
When you urbanize a place, you're not creating flooding on your neighbors adjacent to you.
It provides a buffer for sound, a visual buffer.
It provides an environment for sustaining wildlife.
Just down the street there's a bank building, and between here and the bank building,
It's not uncommon to see deer crossing the road, and it's in a fairly populated area, but the wildlife still is evident here, and it will continue to be that.
Twenty-five percent of the land is being set aside as permanent open space as far as the development plan.
Twenty-five percent?
Twenty-five percent.
Another thing that is different here as compared to other places is when you drive in, you don't see the typical
grocery store on the right and the service station on the left, you have to drive back into the community to village centers to find shopping and retail facilities.
Actually, it's located convenient to where people live.
You just don't drive past it coming in and leaving.
Another thing that is, I think, strikingly different is the

an intensive effort to create economic growth within the community and not be just a residential commuter community, but to give us people an opportunity to live and work in the same environment without the necessity to get in an automobile and drive as great distances as they were.
I guess those are three things that I would say are different.
And the scope of the wooded is different.
The size is 25,000 acres.
Sheenwood is 14,000 acres.
The Woodlands is the largest single land mass, I think, in the world.
Church, you also mentioned the churches.
Wasn't there a concerted effort by the Woodlands Corporation to, in fact, incorporate, invite, in fact, sustain religious and social and, again, these quality of life?
Yeah.
In the early days, there was created something called interfaith.
And interfaith is not a communicable
movement to do away with individual denominations at all.
In Columbia, Maryland, that was attempted, and it failed.
There was only one church.
When you start dealing with the religious community and then doing away with the denominations, you're treading on thin ice.
But here, the Interfaith was an umbrella organization that helped fledgling churches find a site in the woodlands,
We helped them build a building which served as a place for a congregation to meet and to like afford to build a building.
It sort of coordinated the early religious activity with each religious denomination keeping their own identity intact.
And that organization still exists.
It operates a daycare center.
It has an outreach program for senior citizens.
It does a lot of charitable things in addition to coordinating activities for churches.
But right now, I think there are 19 church buildings in the Woodlands that have been built, and some 23 congregations, two or three have not yet built their own sanctuary.
See, I think that's significant.
How do you make money off of churches?
Well, you don't.
You don't, that's right.
But it helps develop a fabric in the community.
That's right, that's right.
And another thing we've done here, and I'm proud of this, I've been involved in this from the outset, we have
had an ongoing program to provide housing for senior citizens.
And it takes various forms.
One, we have subsidized housing for seniors who cannot afford to rent apartments.
So we have some 600, 700 rental apartments that is subsidized.
And that's a negative word in a lot of places, subsidized housing.
And you think how detrimental that would be to other property sizes.
But in fact, it has not been here.
But senior citizens live in rental apartments.
We have a congregate care facility with 300 units in that where people need some assistance in living, but not at the level of a nursing home.
But we do have a nursing home here, too.
And we have four generations of families living in the Woodlands today, and we're only 16 years old.
And it's worked this way.
First,

young couple comes to buy a home they've been transferred here from ohio and they have a couple of young children so that's that's two generations there when their parents retire in ohio instead of moving to florida and not knowing you know in the sun city where you don't know anybody except other people who retired they have elected to come and live close to their children that's really happening and even the great-grandparents have come and their housing opportunities
throughout the woodlands for those four generations.
Not all retirees live in subsidized housing.
Some choose to live by their own home and live independently, just as you and I would do that.
But there's been this concerted effort to create the extended family in reverse.
After World War II, families were scattered across the United States.
grandparents stayed back at home and the kids left and they formed their home in another city.
Kids didn't get to grow up with their grandparents.
I think something happened to society during those years in the 50s and 60s.
Here in the Woodlands, I'm pleased that we're part of bringing some families back together.
True, it's an economic opportunity for us, but also it's a
strengthening their family ties.
Is this basically the essence of your demographic plan, I guess, that it's a family-oriented community?
Well, it's family.
We have a fairly good number of singles that live here.
I think 40% of the families who live here have no children.
And that's a national trend across this country.
Families are waiting later to have children.
Some have none at all.
But
There are also very strong family ties that exist in the community, too.
What about an economic spectrum of society?
Trying to provide something for everyone.
Yeah, as I say, we have subsidized housing for the elderly.
We have subsidized housing for families or individuals who don't qualify for it.
I guess in total there are 1,500 subsidized units in the woods or something like that.
We have more subsidized housing in the Woodlands than any other community in Houston that is a planned community.
Is it subsidized only for the elderly?
No, some for families, low-income families, low- and moderate-income families.
And that's to get a mix?
Yeah.
The social scheme of planning was to provide a broad cross-section of housing opportunities for a heterogeneous population.
That's got to fit the new community.
Yeah, well, that was part of the new community program that was conceived by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Affairs, which failed miserably.
This is the only community out of 13 that was formed under that Title VII new community program that came about in 1971 that succeeded, that did not go into foreclosure.
There are several that are still active, but it was after they went into foreclosure and they did not pay the
on indebtedness that they were obligated to pay.
But this one succeeded, and it succeeded, I think, for some very valid, basic reasons.
One, it was adjacent to a growing metropolitan area.
It was on a major interstate highway that led into the business district, and we were not too far removed from that.
We were close to an international airport.
There was good transportation, there were jobs existing in the local area, and the ones who failed didn't meet those criteria.
It was a social experiment with the notion that if you started a new city out in an isolated part of the world,
people would transfer from the inner city and all those problems they had would go away and they would start life anew and things would be wonderful and great.
But it doesn't work that way.
People who move into this community bring the problems with them that they have.
I think the environment helps them deal with those problems, perhaps, and cope with them.
But it certainly doesn't do away with them.
By having a good school system, and we do have a good public school system, I mentioned private schools,
And that didn't come about out of dissatisfaction with the public schools.
It's just a supplement to the public schools.

But by having a good school system, this growing family relationship, jobs in the local area, I think a good array of recreational opportunities that kids can use as well as adults, the involvement of churches in the community, and the establishment of traditional institutions
the YMCA, the YWCA, the Kiwanis Club, the Lions Club, the Rotary Club.
All of those kind of things have come together in a very nice way here in the Woodlands.
Let me ask you one other question.
You piqued my curiosity.
I've heard four times now, and it's all exactly the same.
One of the reasons why the Woodlands succeeded with us together is because it's close to a major metropolitan area.
It's on the interstate.
It's next to the airport.
Did that come out of...
an in-house study?
Was there an independent study?
Because everyone we've talked to says the same thing.
Well, maybe we were lucky we bought the land in the right place.
George Mitchell, once again, in an attempt to diversify his own company, which was predominantly oil and gas, and still is largely oil and gas, saw the growing north side of Houston as a

as a real estate development opportunity and he started acquiring lands here in the early 60s through the mid-60s and there were a number of large timber companies that owned sizable tracts of land and taxes and other reasons made it non-productive for timber use and george bought a lot of land for a very reasonable price and i don't think
George may disagree with it, but I don't think George knew exactly what he was going to do when he was buying it.

He had not formulated all the plans, but he knew that the north side of Houston was intercontinental airport, interstate highway to Dallas, the wooded environment, the low cost of land at that time, the growth of Houston.
